She turned to a blank page and wrote the date. Below, she wrote "11/05/648 - 13/12/648."
"Are you rereading memories?" Ivory asked, looking at the old notebook. Kari nodded. "Do you think they'll let you out for Christmas? It's only a few days away."
Kari tapped twice on the lantern. No. Ivory had been right. The Ice King never let Kari out, because she was "a mistake" in his eyes. She was born mute, and she was the only girl in the family, which otherwise consisted only of boys.
Ivory was one too, in her own way. When she had revealed her non-binary identity, it was as if the world had changed too. She was given tasks that condemned her to loneliness, as punishment for her difference.
Iel also had to stay in service to the princess, but it wasn't a big deal, because it gave her a friend.
"It's almost your birthday, isn't it?" Ivory asked, remembering that the princess's birthday was coming up in a few days. Kari nodded, a sad glint in her pale blue eyes.
"Do you want to celebrate it?" As she asked the question, Iel remembered what she had answered the last time.
No, Kari replied touchingly. Ivory knew it was a difficult subject for her. It was the day she had been confined to her room and her mother had been banished. Ivory was still a baby when it happened, but Iel remembered the outrage of the servants and the townspeople. Iel had heard that Queen Eirwen was a good queen, but that she also had this strange ability to predict the future.
"Well... what do you want to do?" Iel asked. Kari looked up with enthusiasm. She handed Iel a piece of paper. But when Iel looked at it...
15 cm x 15 cm painting paper
White, several shades of blue paint
6 brushes of different sizes
Easel
"Do you want me to get these things for you?" Ivory said, turning to the silent princess who was frantically tapping, shaking her braids back and forth. "Yes?" Iel giggled slightly at seeing the usually reserved princess become passionate about something. It was the first time she had asked for something unrelated to books and that wasn't in her room.
"Okay. See you later?" Ivory offered, standing up and making her way through the pile of papers and notebooks.
Kari nodded and immersed herself in her memories again, wrapping herself in her thick blanket.
Iel stepped out of the room with relief. The princess was finally stepping out of her comfort zone by asking for things that were not within her realm, like paint.
Iel turned back through the corridors, trying not to listen to the whispers of the servants.
"I've heard she's possessed by Queen Eirwen, that's why she always goes into that room."
"I've heard she eats children in this room."
"She looks like a man, doesn't she?"
Iel covered their ears, because trying to ignore them didn't work. Iel headed toward the royal painter's room, which was in the east wing, second door on the left.
Ivory approached the door, which was just as intricately carved as Kari's. It bore a white dragon, one of the six primordial dragons, who according to legend had created Frostfell. It was normal for the painter to display it on his door. He liked the story.
Iel opened the door, expecting to find a normal scene. Paint splatters everywhere, pencils and papers scattered around the room, easels covering every last centimeter of the wall. Surprisingly, iel saw none of this. The room was clean and there was a red velvet background with a stool just in front. On the stool sat Prince Aquilo, who was having his portrait painted.
"Ah hello, Ivory! Come to watch your future king pose for a portrait?" asked Aquilo to Ivory, giving her a wink.
"Excuse me, little prince," Iel replied, partially ignoring him in search of the objects his silent friend desired. "I'm just here to get supplies."
"Ah, the little girl is going to leave very soon?" asked Aquilo, "But I wanted to see you!"
"Well, not me." Ivory had found the art supplies from her list and placed them in a box she had found. "And I'm not a girl."
The prince hadn't thought about it, however. "Oh my dear, you know it's just a phase! It will pass when you grow up!" he muttered.
"I need to go," Iel said suddenly, feeling uncomfortable because of the prince's words, which reminded her of all the bad things people said about her gender identity. I really want to distance myself from him."
"Are you leaving already?" The Prince appeared immediately at the door, ignoring the royal painter's complaints.
"That's not the behavior of a future king!" Iel reprimanded him.
"No one will know. The others won't believe you, and the painter will say nothing if he values his life." He turned back to the painter for a second, then leaned toward Ivory. "What do you say to a date?" Iel shivered. Certainly, Iel had received many threats in the past, but never from a prince, let alone the heir to the throne.
"Don't you know what the word 'no' means?" Iel shouted, shoving the prince out of the way.
"Oh no," replied Aquilo with a smile. Obviously, the prince who gets everything he wants doesn't know what the word means.
Ivory rolled her eyes. "Why want a date with me instead of others? You must have a hundred suitors?"
He interrupted her, still smiling: "500, to be exact." He threw his hair back, making it fly in the cold air.
"So, why me instead of another? I'm the threat to the palace." Iel wrapped her arms around her body.
"You are the most beautiful girl I have ever seen." Aquilo placed his finger under her chin and forced Ivory to look at him.
